                      <span>2003-01-06</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>On the Tao Te Ching portion of the book: This elucidation by Ni is supposed to represent the Southern Internal Alchemy school's view on the Tao Te Ching.  This version is not as poetic or beautiful as some others, but is clear and effective in delivering its message, without confusing the reader too much.<br>On the Hua Hu Ching portion of the book: I do not like this portion of the book.  The message may be valuable, but the format is in that of a conversation between Laozi and a prince, and is old fashioned in language so it is confusing and harder to understand.  This is just my opinion, and some of my friends enjoyed this format, and maybe you will too, but I prefer Brian Walker's version, which is based on this very translation, but is instead a sort of poetic summary, condensing each chapter to its essential lessons.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Good book!</div>
